segments.text: First, Dr. Quisenberry, tell us something about your early life, including the names of your parents, the places and dates of their birth and death, the place and date of your birth, and the schools you attended before enrolling at Texas A&M.
Well, I can't give you the dates on my father and mother's birth and death, but I could give you the place of birth.
My father was born in McKinney, Texas.
His father migrated to Texas rather early in the history of Texas, and he was born there
My mother was born in Tennessee, and they settled in Gainesville, Texas, after their marriage, and I was born in Gainesville.
I was the...
I had three brothers and two sisters.
I'm next to the youngest in the family.
I have a sister who is living in Grand Prairie at the present time who is younger than I am.
And then when I was two years old,
I was born in June 25, 1907.
And when I was two years old, that would mean in 1909, my parents moved to what I call West Texas.
It was really Hardeman County.
at the lower end of the Panhandle, you know, Texas Panhandle.
And they lived on a rented farm for a few years, and then my father bought 320 acres of land.
The family moved on to this, and we attended a rural school at that time.
It was called Friendship School.
That was the name of the precinct or school.
And it was a two-room school.
And then later on, they enlarged it and made a three-room school out of it.
And I went to this school until I was in my tenth.
Actually, in those days, we had eleven grades in Texas.
I believe today we have twelve, but in those days, eleven.

and I attended through my 10th grade, and they did not teach the 11th grade, and so I transferred into the county seat, Quanna, Texas, for my senior year, and graduated from Quanna High School in 1927.
Could you give us the names of your parents?
Yes, my mother was, her maiden name was Nancy Lane, and my father was Walter Henry Quisenberry, W.H.
Quisenberry.
And they...
My father, I'm very bad about memory and dates, but my mother died first and she's been dead probably about ten years and my father's been dead about six years, I imagine.
What type of farming did your father do?
It was general, diversified farming.
Most of the crops, the cash crop was majorly cotton, but he grew also a little bit of corn, not much corn, mostly grain sorghum, and then he grew almost always, if the
the rainfall was adequate.
He nearly always had wheat, and once in a while he would have a little bit of oats.
But mostly, well I should have said cash crop also, the wheat was majorly a cash crop, wheat and cotton, but the grain sorghum was used for feeding.
We had dairy cattle where we had a little more than
the milk and butter for the family, and so a little bit was sold as cream, usually.
And then we had horses, the early part.
In fact, practically all through my farming days, we did not have tractor mechanical power.
It was mostly horse and mule power.
I guess that is the major essence of it.
He had some pasture land where the dairy cattle were turned out for grazing in the grass.
And then, of course, they were fed usually cottonseed meal and hulls for protein sources, and then probably milo or grain sorghum for their concentrate.
Did he do any irrigating at all?
Not at that time.
There was no irrigation.
We did have a well and a windmill that supplied the... We didn't have electric power extension, REA power at that time.
And so we had a windmill that pumped the water for the cattle, for the livestock, let's say.
It was, in that area, the water is what we call gyp water.
It's a hard, extremely hard water and not very good for drinking.
And so most of our drinking water was caught
by a gutter on the house and run into a underground cistern to keep it cool.
And that's the type of water we drank.
And also it was that type of water was used mostly for washing the dishes and the clothes and so on.
What factors were involved in your choice of Texas A&M?
Well, I had a county agent
in my county under whom I had an agriculture project as a high school youngster.
And he was a Texas A&M graduate.
I also had a vocational agriculture teacher.
I took vocational agriculture my senior year in high school as one of my subjects, and I didn't have a VOAG project as such.
But he was also from Texas A&M, and I dare say, if I were real honest, I would say that these two people, as in almost every case, the older we get, the more we realize how important people are
in this world and how unimportant a lot of other things that we think earlier is quite important becomes, if you part a little philosophy at this stage.

But nevertheless, I think these two menmy father had favoredTexas Tech had just been established a little bit before that, and I think living out near in the western part of the state, I think my father would have probably been a little happier if I had gone to Texas Tech.
But I think I definitely preferred to come to A&M myself as far as opportunities for coursework and so on were concerned.
And as I said, these two men also reinforced any tendency I might have had.
I'm a little bit interested in your comment that you did not have an agricultural project in your Vocational Agriculture course.
You remember when I took Vocational Agriculture in high school,
it was a requirement.
Either you had a project or you didn't pass the course.
Well, as I recall it, I may be confused here.
I may have been mixing up my 4-H county agent project with my VAWAG project.
I know I had Green Sargum as my project in high school.
This I know.
And it may be that I did some
inadvertent switching of the credit for that.
So I may have also had a requirement at that time.
What were your first reactions to A&M and College Station when you arrived?
as an incoming freshman?
Well, you're talking to a person that is a little bit different from probably the typical one you'd talk to.
It happens that when I was a freshman in high school, I came down with diabetes.
And so I was a bit, I had to watch, and I had to take insulin.

If Banning and Best had not discovered insulin when they did, if they'd have been six months later in discovering and actually making available on the market, they didn't make available at the company, they did.
making available insulin, I would definitely not be here.
I would have another three months and I would have been dead because I had already gone before the discovery.
I'd already gone just about as far as I could possibly have gone.
And so as a result of it, I lost almost a year in high school.
And then I started taking insulin.
And as long as I was at home,
I, through my tenth grade, my mother looked after my diet, a very rich diet.
And then in my senior year, a very fine couple, a county judge and his wife, who happened to be, he had married during World War I, an English girl.
And they invited me to live in their home in Kwana.
And so I cooked my own meals and went to school.

And so when I came to A&M, it happened that the county agent, the man I'd had as a county agent, had actually been employed as an instructor in the animal science, or at that time it was animal husbandry department, at Texas A&M.
And the instructional unit of the animal husbandry department, they had a swine herd.
It was right out in the middle of where the golf course is at the present time.
And the herdsman for the swine herd was a veteran.
of World War I, and he had been severely injured.
He'd never married.
He was a bachelor.
And he'd been severely injured with gas, toxic gas, during World War I.
And he lived there, and this county agent contacted him and asked him about the possibility of my having a room, and so I could prepare my meals.
and go to school.
And he said he'd be delighted to have company and made it possible.
So I came with my brothers.
Two of my brothers brought me to A&M and installed me in the residence.
And this is the way I started the school.
And so that was my first impression.
There was no intention of every...
Well, I knew that advanced education was essential.
I'd probably never be a very successful farmer, physically.
And so for that reason, I had made up my mind, this is what had to be.
Your older brothers, then, I take it, had not gone to college.
No, no.
In fact, of my brothers and sisters, I'm the only one that graduated from a university, a college or university.
But your two older brothers accompanied you to College Station and installed you in the...
They brought me here with the necessary utensils for preparing my meals and so on.
So that's what started it.
I'm assuming you came by train?
No, by car, by automobile.
How long a trip was it?
We took two days to come to College Station.
We stopped on the way in Fort Worth.
I spent the night in Fort Worth and then to College Station the next day.
Did you stay all four years with this herdsman?
No, I stayed two years with the herdsman, and then he became ill and had to quit his job.
He lived over in the hill country, Schertz.
or Cibolo, Texas, and he had some sisters there.
He went back.
And Mr. D.W. Williams, you possibly know, he served in almost every capacity in this institution, including acting chancellor and so on.
But Mr. D.W. Williams was head of the animal husbandry department at that time.
And when this man left the farm, I had to leave the farm residence.
And so Mr. Williams made possible, moved some books around and what have you in one of the rooms here in the old Animal Husbandly Judging Pavilion.
And he gave me that, called me the custodian.
And incidentally, this is a story that is not easy to forget.
I lived in this corner of the, that would be the northeast corner, of the old judging pavilion during my junior year.
And Tiger Teague, whom everybody in this county knows, I think, lived in the south corner
That would be the southwest corner of the Judging Pavilion.
So we were in opposite corners of the Judging Pavilion one year.
So we have a lot in common in that regard.
And where did you live your senior year?
The man came back.
He recovered and came back to the swine farm.
And so he asked me if I wouldn't move back out.
And so I did and lived back at the swine farm during my senior year.
Were there very many students who lived outside of the dormitories?
Oh, no.
Almost all of the students lived in the dormitory, and almost 100% of the students were cadets.
I was a cadet, but I was a day student.
In those days, they called them day students, those who lived outside the dormitories.
This is exaggerating a little bit because I have no justification in terms of the treatment I received.
But as you know, the old common statement is that a day student was the lowest form of life in those days.
But that was not so in my case.
I was in F Company infantry for my two years.
I couldn't take advanced because, you know, it required a contract, and being diabetic, they would not give me a contract.
So I took the first two years of military science, and I was in F Company infantry, and the boys knew why I was a day student.
And they were a very wonderful bunch of boys in my organization to me.
So for that reason, I never had any enmity or resentment against the Cadet Corps of Military Science.
Now, did you participate in the drill?
Yes.
Oh, you bet.
Yes, indeed.
I always made drill.
I wore the uniform all the time.
and then I participated in the first two years.
The last two years you wore civilian clothes?
Well, my junior year I wore civilian clothes.
Then in the senior year, the college changed its policy and required that civilian students wear a uniform.
They had what they called an Aggie uniform.
We wore everything, the same uniform, except we didn't have the insignia, the military insignia.
So I did...

rejoin, and since I had to wear a uniform, I rejoined my military organization and did wear the insignia for theI was not under contract or anything of that sort, but I didwas back in the cadet corps my senior year, but I still was a day student.
And for all of the four years you cooked all of your own meals?
Yes, yes indeed.
And even though you were on a strict diet, you also continued to take insulin?
Yes, oh yes.
I still take insulin.
I've taken, probably one of the very few that can say that they have taken insulin for more than 50 years, because not very many diabetics live that long.
Living...
outside the dormitory as you did, say particularly in your freshman year and being in the corps, were, I'm assuming since you were not in the dormitory, you were
in a sense, excused from or avoided a lot of the hassling that some of the freshmen went through, like making beds and cleaning rifles and that sort of thing?
Yes, they did not force me to do this at first until they learned, until the whole organization learned.
why I was a day student.
I got some of the other things that, you used a kind word of hassling on it, but it didn't take very long.
The captain of the company knew, soon learned, why I was a day student.
And then he informed and probably issued a few orders to
to particularly the sophomores in the company.
What did the students of your day do for entertainment and recreation?
Well, I'll tell you, in those days, I believe we studied longer hours than we do today.
I believe the professorsthis would be prejudiced answerbut I believe the professors were harder on us than they are today.
Well, I know that the fellows in the dormitories had an enforced study period, but of course you were not in a dormitory.
And you had somewhat irregular hours from them, I guess.
You did not have an enforced study period, but then you also did not have anybody to bother you, I presume.
No, but I did study.
And being, I think, probably the ability to study without any interference also made it possible for me to make exceptionally good grades.
Did the school provide any kind of entertainment, such as movies, theatrical performances, and so forth?
Yes, yes, there was.
There were two sources of movies.
There was the old assembly hall, which is located now.
I believe probably Lowy and Puryear dormitories right at the back part of them was where the old assembly hall was located right in there, right opposite where the new hospital building is.
And you had movies there.
Yeah, they had movies there.
I think, I'm not sure whether it was only weekly or whether it was nightly.
This I don't know because I didn't go to very many movies for two reasons.
I was in school from 1927 to 1931.
And you may not be old enough to know, but 1931 was the...
age of the maximum depression that you could have.
So dollars were very, very scarce indeed, and so they had to be saved.
And you said there were two sources.
One was the assembly hall.
And I believe that the Guyon Hall at that time was also used for some recreational material.
Did you have any favorite instructors?
Yes.
I don't know whether if you ask me to name them, I'm not sure I could name them all, and I'm not sure I'd want to name them all, but the answer would be a positive yes.
You're probably going to ask me what the characteristics of those professors were.
Well, I was going to say if you could name any of them.
Did any of the faculty members have some influence on your leaning towards work with poultry?
Well, I think Mr. D.W. Williams, I took a course under him, and he was a very excellent professor and helped in this direction to lean toward animal science, the broad field of animal science.
Povey came in later in the graduate level, not as an undergraduate, but at the graduate level.
And then I can name a couple more, and I'd like to do it, as a matter of fact.
My English professor, most ag students, as you know, are a little reluctant to welcome their English courses.
But to me, my English courses were some of my most enjoyable courses.
I'd had a very excellent English teacher in high school.
So she had been successful in indoctrinating me.
It wasn't an indoctrination.
It was really a challenge to me to do English well.
And so Mr. P.G.
Gutter was one of my, he's long since dead now, but I enjoyed Mr. Gutter as a Sunday school teacher after I came back here for a number of years on the faculty.
but he was after his retirement, before and after his retirement.
But he was a very excellent English teacher, and I enjoyed very much courses under him.
And then another English teacher was the former librarian.
You probably have heard his name, and I don't think you have probably ever met him, but Tommy Mayo, who was the librarian.
I had a course, and it was an unusual course for English.
It could well have been taught in other departments, but it happened to be taught in English and taught by a very fine teacher, and it was called Modern Civilization.
And what we did, we went through a number of new books describing what was to come.
And as you can imagine, a youngster at that age, they liked to use their imagination.
And so that type of course was quite a challenge.
I remember very distinctly those courses as being excellent, very much enjoyed.
And was the Modern Civilization an elective or a required course?
Oh, no, it's selective.
Oh, yes, selective, yes.
But you did have one hour.
one year of English as a requirement.
I believe in those days we had two years of required English, yes.
But I took some additional elective courses.
I know that for a long period the entire Corps was assembled on Sunday morning and marched to chapel.
Was that still a practice when you were a student?
Yes, I believe it was.
I believe it was.
And they had chapel in Guyon Hall, too.
And so you had to get up and join your company?
No, no, I didn't.
I was excused from this.
I went to Sunday school in church, but I did it on my own.
Being a day student, I was not required to make that.
I did have to make the military, too.
In those days, the drill was on Tuesdays, and I did have to make all of those.
Tuesday afternoons?
Yes.
That was your only day of drill?
Yes, I believe that's right, yes.
You said you went to Sunday school and church.
Did you go in Guyon Hall or did you go to one of the churches off campus?
No, I went to a local church.
At the time that you were a student, what was the general attitude of the students towards the university administration or college administration?
Having been on both sides, I hope you'll forgive me for adding a few extra words onto this.

But I think in general, the students thought that if there was one thing that could be dispensed with in their college training, those days it was Texas A&M, so college or university training, it would have been the administration.
But I don't think that's changed too much.
I believe it's a little more acceptable today than it was then, but there's still a tendency for it to be that way.
We know that a lot of students during the years have had part-time jobs, and you have
were custodian, or indicated you were custodian of the Animal Husbandry Pavilion for your junior year, I believe.
Yes.
Did you have other jobs during the other years that you were a student?
Yes, indeed.
In fact, that year, the custodian was really an earning of the...
of the room, the space where I lived.
In addition to this, that same year I had to work because I
I had practically no source of income.
My parents, it was in the days when they just did not have money, and I was from a fairly large family.
And so I worked for twenty-five cents an hour.
They gave me work at the swine farm, and I worked there the first two years, and then I worked there during my junior year when I lived in the pavilion.
And then I worked also in my senior year.
I worked all four years at 25 cents an hour.
Now, in addition to that, there was some earning.
I collected specimens for the botany professor, Dr. Ball.
He's long.
He was head of the department.
But I collected specimens.
And then a part of a year, I worked part time in cleaning up the agricultural engineering shops after the classes.
